Before a homograph check can take place,
it is necessary to build a library of homographs to
check against in the first place. This was done
using a script that compared two corpuses and
identifying words that existed across both
corpuses. For instance, to identify homographs that exist across the Malay and English language, one might
feed a dictionary list of both Malay and English
words to identify the words that exist across both these
languages. These words are then recorded and sorted alphabetically into an array of JSON objects.
At this stage of the process, the list of languages detected in the previous process plays a significant
role. The process of homograph detection works on a simple principle:
For every language detected within a
sample sentence, each word of that same sentence will be tested against that list of languages for the presence
of homographs.
